R graph cookbook

R Markdown

This is an R Markdown document. Markdown is a simple formatting syntax for authoring HTML, PDF, and MS Word documents. For more details on using R Markdown see http://rmarkdown.rstudio.com.

When you click the Knit button a document will be generated that includes both content as well as the output of any embedded R code chunks within the document. You can embed an R code chunk like this:

summary(cars)
##      speed           dist       
##  Min.   : 4.0   Min.   :  2.00  
##  1st Qu.:12.0   1st Qu.: 26.00

##  3rd Qu.:19.0   3rd Qu.: 56.00  
##  Max.   :25.0   Max.   :120.00

R graph cookbook examples

library(dplyr,verbose = FALSE)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
library(ggplot2)
plot(mtcars$wt, mtcars$mpg)

using ggplot2 to plot

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = wt, y = mpg)) + 
    geom_point()

or

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(data = NULL, aes(x = mtcars$wt, y = mtcars$mpg)) + 
    geom_point()

plot the line

plot(pressure$temperature, pressure$pressure, type = 'l')
points(pressure$temperature, pressure$pressure, col = "red")

ggplot(pressure, aes(x = temperature, y = pressure)) + 
    geom_line() +
    geom_point(color='red')

2.3 Creating a Bar Graph

barplot

BOD
##   Time demand
## 1    1    8.3
## 2    2   10.3
## 3    3   19.0
## 4    4   16.0
## 5    5   15.6
## 6    7   19.8
barplot(BOD$demand, names.arg = BOD$Time)

when the x is continuous

ggplot(BOD, aes(x = Time, y = demand)) + 
    geom_col()

when the x is discrete

ggplot(BOD, aes(x = factor(Time), y = demand)) + 
    geom_col()

create a histogram

hist(mtcars$mpg, breaks = 8)

ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = mpg)) + 
    geom_histogram(binwidth = 4)

create a boxplot

plot(ToothGrowth$supp, ToothGrowth$len)

boxplot(len ~ supp, data = ToothGrowth)

ggplot(ToothGrowth, aes(x = supp, y = len)) + 
    geom_boxplot()
